Investigating the Colleges and Universities Data Set¶

The Colleges and Universities data can be found here: https://hifld-geoplatform.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/colleges-and-universities

Overview of Contents:¶

  2. Choosing the Question to Answer

What are "X" and "Y"?¶

Comparing X and Y to longitude and latitude shows that X is longitude and Y is latitude.

In [10]:
# The output below shows that the X is approximately Longitude and Y is approximately Latitude
print(np.unique(np.round(data.X.astype(str).astype(float),2) == np.round(data.LONGITUDE,2)))
print(np.unique(np.round(data.Y.astype(str).astype(float),2) == np.round(data.LATITUDE,2)))

What is the "Population" variable?¶

Population numbers are derived by adding Total Employees and Total Enrollment together, where -999 values are most likely missing values.

In [11]:
# The output below shows that the population is equal to the sum of the total enrolled and the total employees
df_pop = data[['POPULATION', 'TOT_ENROLL','TOT_EMP']].replace(-999, 0)
print(np.unique(df_pop.POPULATION == df_pop.TOT_ENROLL + df_pop.TOT_EMP))

As with all data projects, a specific question needs to be asked in order to select a data strategy and solve the business problem. Now some exploratory data analysis has been conducted, a question can be formulated.

2. Choosing The Question to Answer¶

A common issue in education is having enough teachers, or staff, to accommodate the needs of each student. With the given data set, we can pose the following question:

The Question: Which schools are most accommodating for students?¶

This question can be tackled by creating new metrics, using exploratory analysis, and implementing unsupervised learning methods.

In [14]:
'''
Create a new dataframe 
where number of full-time students enrolled and number of employees is greater than zero, or not missing.
'''
df = data[data.TOT_ENROLL > 0][data.TOT_EMP > 0]
print("There were {} schools dropped in the analysis.".format(data.shape[0] - df.shape[0]))

There were 735 schools dropped in the analysis.

Create a new metric to measure level of accommodation¶

The ratio between total enrolled students and total employees will be the metric for calculating how accomodating a school is. A higher ratio would suggest that each employee has to accommodate more students on average, which means the school would be less able to accomodate every student's needs. The total enrollment feature was selected over the part-time or full-time enrollment feature to account for all students' needs.

In [15]:
# Create a new feature to represent the student to employee ratio called RATIO 
df['RATIO'] = df.TOT_ENROLL / df.TOT_EMP
In [16]:
# Look at the distribution of student to employee ratios

Some information we gain from looking at the pairwise plot and correlation coefficient values:

  • There is a very strong positive linear relationship between the number of full-time enrolled students (FT_ENROLL) and total dormitory capacity (DORM_CAP) due to the high correlation coefficient value denoted as "r".
  • Schools with higher enrollment or higher total employees tend to be level 1 and 2 schools.
  • Schools with higher total dormitory capacity tend to be level 1 schools.

Understanding the Ordinal Features¶

Since the ordinal features have several anomalies where the values are negative, I decided to see if there was a difference in the correlation between these features.

In [24]:
# Select the features that are ordinal
ordinal_features = ['TYPE','SECTOR','LEVEL_','HI_OFFER','LOCALE','SIZE_SET','INST_SIZE']
# Subset the data on the ordinal features
ordinal_df = df[ordinal_features]
# Replace the negative values with NULL for easier removal using dropna function
ordinal_df[ordinal_df < 0] = np.nan
print("There were {} schools dropped in the analysis due to negative values.".format(ordinal_df.shape[0] - ordinal_df.dropna().shape[0]))

There were 2534 schools dropped in the analysis due to negative values.

Looking at the two correlation plots, it is clear that the negative values in the data have negligible effect on the correlation of the features because the features that are correlated in one plot are also correlated in the other. Therefore, we can say that the following feature pairs show the following relationships:


Strong positive linear relationship:

  • LEVEL & SECTOR
  • SIZE SET & HI OFFER


Strong negative linear relationship:

  • HI OFFER & SECTOR
  • HI OFFER & LEVEL
  • SIZE SET & SECTOR
  • SIZE SET & LEVEL

3. Principal Component Analysis¶

To implement PCA on the data, we first need to normalize the data and scale to unit variance. It is also important to not include features that are linear combinations of other features, which are Population and Total Enrollment in this case.

In [27]:
'''
Normalize data for PCA
'''
# Normalize data and drop features that are linear combinations of other features
X = preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(df[numerical_columns].drop(['POPULATION','TOT_ENROLL'], axis=1))
In [28]:
# Initiate with a large number of components
pca = PCA(n_components=11)
# Get the project PCA scores
projected = pca.fit_transform(X)
In [29]:
plt.plot(pca.explained_variance_ratio_, marker='o')
plt.title('Scree Plot', fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel('Number of Principal Components', fontsize=15)
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance', fontsize=15)
plt.show()

The number of principal components to use is determined at the point beyond which the additional explained variance are all relatively small and of comparable size. In the scree plot, this number of principal components to use corresponds to 4. Therefore, four principal components will be used in the analysis.

In [30]:
# Refit PCA on 4 principal components and create dataframe for biplot
reduced_data = PCA(n_components=4).fit_transform(X)
reduced_data = pd.DataFrame(reduced_data, columns = ['PC 1', 'PC 2', 'PC 3', 'PC 4'])
In [31]:
'''
Biplot function
'''
def biplot(data, reduced_data, pca):
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (14,8))
    
    # Scatterplot of the reduced data 
    ax.scatter(x=reduced_data.loc[:, 'PC 1'], y=reduced_data.loc[:, 'PC 2'], facecolors='violet', edgecolors='violet', s=70, alpha=0.5)
    
    feature_vectors = pca.components_.T

    # Use scaling factors to make the arrows
    arrow_size, text_pos = 10.0, 11.0

    # Projections of the original features
    for i, v in enumerate(feature_vectors):
        ax.arrow(0, 0, arrow_size*v[0], arrow_size*v[1], head_width=0.2, head_length=0.2, linewidth=2, color='red')
        ax.text(v[0]*text_pos, v[1]*text_pos, df[numerical_columns].drop(['POPULATION','TOT_ENROLL'], axis=1).columns[i], color='black', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=10)

    ax.set_xlabel("Principal Component 1", fontsize=18)
    ax.set_ylabel("Principal Component 2", fontsize=18)
    ax.set_title("PC 1 vs PC 2 Plane with Original Feature Projections", fontsize=20);
    return ax

biplot(df, reduced_data, pca)
Out[31]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x271aa9c7828>

Interpretation of principal components is based on finding which features are most strongly correlated with each component, i.e., which of these numbers are large in magnitude, the farthest from zero in either direction.

Based on the principal components table and biplot, the following interpretation can be made:

Principal Component 1 (PC 1) represents approximately 50% of the variation in the data set. The higher positive PC 1 scores represent higher values in HI OFFER and SIZE SET. The negative PC 1 scores represent lower values in SECTOR and LEVEL.

This suggests that schools with high PC 1 scores have higher highest offers and Carnegie Classification numbers with relatively lower institution sector numbers, and institution level numbers.

Principal Component 2 (PC 2) represents approximately 16% of the variation in the data set. The positive scores represents FT ENROLL and TOT_EMP. The negative scores represent higher values in HI OFFER.

This suggests that schools with high PC 2 scores have relatively higher full-time enrollment and total employees with relatively lower highest offer.


PC 1 and 2 represent the most variation in the data, so the interpretation of PC 1 and 2 will be the main takeaways from this PCA.



Additional interpretation of other principal components:

Principal Component 3 (PC 3) represents approximately 10% of the variation in the data set. The positive scores represents TYPE. The negative scores represent higher values in LOCALE.

This suggests that schools with high PC 3 scores have higher institution type numbers with relatively lower degree of urbanization.

Principal Component 4 (PC 4) represents approximately 8% of the variation in the data set. The positive scores represents PT ENROLL. The negative scores represent higher values in LOCALE.

This suggests that schools with high PC 4 scores have higher part-time enrollment with relatively lower values in degree of urbanization.

</i>

plt.xlabel('Principal Component 1 ({}%)'.format(np.round(pca.explained_variance_ratio_[0]*100)), fontsize=25)

plt.colorbar()

This score plot confirms the interpretation made for PC 1 by showing that the lower PC 1 scores are represented by the higher institution sector and the higher scores are represented by lower institution sector (decreasing left to right).

Summary of Insights & the Data-Driven Story¶

The original question is which schools are most accommodating for students?

While many of the insights drawn from exploratory analysis and PCA overlap, the overarching insight is that schools with better accommodation based on the student-employee ratio have:

  • higher highest offers
  • higher Carnegie Classification numbers
  • lower institution sector numbers
  • lower institution level numbers

Other insights:

  • Most colleges, universities, and professional schools are accommodating. They have higher highest offers and lower institution levels, which are correlated to higher Carnegie Classifications and lower sector numbers. Schools with higher total dormitory capacity tend to have lower institution levels, which suggests that this school category also has higher enrollment and total dormitory capacity, which covers a different type of accommodation.

Answer to the original question:

  • Colleges, universities, and professional schools are most accommodating based on the student-employee ratio and would most likely provide living accommodations in dormitories with more students enrolled full-time.
